SIMPLE: nerve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: nerve
<hw>nerve</hw> <pr>(n⟦etil⟧rv)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nerfe</ets>, F. <ets>nerf</ets>, L. <ets>nervus</ets>, akin to Gr.
<grk>ney^ron</grk> sinew, nerve; cf. <grk>neyra`</grk> string,
bowstring; perh. akin to E. <ets>needle</ets>. Cf.
<er>Neuralgia</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of
the whitish and elastic bundles of fibers, with the accompanying
tissues, which transmit nervous impulses between nerve centers and
various parts of the animal body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ An ordinary nerve is made up of several bundles of nerve
fibers, each bundle inclosed in a special sheath (the
<xex>perineurium</xex>) and all bound together in a connective tissue
sheath and framework (the <partof>epineurium</partof>) containing blood
vessels and lymphatics.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sinew or a tendon.</def>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Physical force or steadiness; muscular power and
control; constitutional vigor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>he led me on to mightiest deeds,⟦br⟧
Above the <qex>nerve</qex> of mortal arm.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Steadiness and firmness of mind; self-command in
personal danger, or under suffering; unshaken courage and endurance;
coolness; pluck; resolution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Audacity; assurance.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the principal fibrovascular
bundles or ribs of a leaf, especially when these extend straight from
the base or the midrib of the leaf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the nervures, or veins, in
the wings of insects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nerve cell</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a neuron,
one of the nucleated cells with which nerve fibers are connected; a
<stype>ganglion cell</stype> is one type of nerve cell.</cd> --
<col><b>Nerve fiber</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>one of the fibers
of which nerves are made up. These fibers are either
<stype>medullated</stype> or <stype>nonmedullated</stype>. In both kinds
the essential part is the translucent threadlike <part>axis
cylinder</part> which is continuous the whole length of the fiber.</cd>
-- <col><b>Nerve stretching</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>the
operation of stretching a nerve in order to remedy diseases such as
tetanus, which are supposed to be influenced by the condition of the
nerve or its connections.</cd></cs><-- #!? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nerve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nerve
<hw>Nerve</hw> <pr>(n⟦etil⟧rv)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Nerved</conjf> <pr>(n⟦etil⟧rvs)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Nerving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To give strength or
vigor to; to supply with force; <as>as, fear <ex>nerved</ex> his
arm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nerved</ent>⟦br⟧
